  "read": "TileLang remains promising because it replaced the original many-to-one global atomic pattern with a compact reduced-row contract: raw selected FP32 write volume is modeled at 4 GiB, while the retained compact partial stream is 128 MiB and final dKV is 2 MiB. However, rocprof shows the current retained 8.13 ms path is not blocked by the TileLang panel-dense final fold, which is only about 0.05-0.07 ms. The bottleneck is compact_partial_prim_kernel itself. Its steady dispatches are about 8.05-8.13 ms and issue roughly 928.5M instructions, with LDS (~318.9M), VALU (~272.7M), SALU (~96.6M), branch (~45.6M), and VMEM read (~51.2M) instruction streams surrounding only ~41.9M BF16 MFMA instructions. The generated kernel uses a 160 KiB dynamic shared-memory table per CTA, and the profile reports substantial LDS bank conflict pressure (~0.344 bank conflicts per LDS active index). So the next speed lever is not the final ScatterAdd/fold; it is reducing the producer-side LDS staging, slot/index scalar work, and local active-group accumulation traffic while preserving query-major MFMA reuse.",
  "decision": "keep_tilelang_branch_promoted_for_contract_but_rewrite_producer_layout",
  "next_kernel_targets": [
    "Reduce or eliminate the 512x64 FP32 LDS active-group table per CTA; use smaller row-block/register-owned accumulators or two-level micro reducers.",
    "Keep query-major q/dO reuse, but make selected-slot accumulation less LDS-heavy than the current dynamic PairSlots -> 160KiB LDS table path.",
    "Fuse or stream LI/probability production later for correctness/memory; do not expect that alone to close the measured 8 ms producer wall.",
    "Treat panel-dense fold as solved for now; optimizing it further has sub-0.1 ms upside."
  ],
  "rocprof_docs": "https://rocm.docs.amd.com/projects/rocprofiler-sdk/en/latest/how-to/using-rocprofv3.html"
}
